  "prompt": "What three books should an economics undergraduate read?",
  "response": "Here are three foundational books that every economics undergraduate should consider reading:\n\n1. **\"The Wealth of Nations\" by Adam Smith** - Often regarded as the cornerstone of classical economics, this book provides essential insights into the workings of free markets, the division of labor, and the role of self-interest in promoting economic prosperity. Its historical context and foundational ideas remain relevant in understanding economic theory.\n\n2. **\"Principles of Economics\" by Gregory Mankiw** - This textbook covers a wide range of economic principles, from microeconomics to macroeconomics, in an accessible way. Mankiw's clear explanations and real-world examples make complex concepts easier to understand, making it a staple for introductory economics courses.\n\n3. **\"Capital in the Twenty-First Century\" by Thomas Piketty** - This contemporary work explores income inequality and wealth distribution over the past few centuries, examining the relationship between economic growth and inequality. Piketty's analysis offers valuable insights into modern economic challenges and has sparked significant discussions about policy and economics in the 21st century.\n\nThese books provide a strong foundation in both the historical and contemporary aspects of economics, laying the groundwork for further study in the field.",
